statement.p:
Let A be a 2 \times 2 matrix with a non-real eigenvalue 2+3i. Explain how to find a 2 \times 2 matrix P such that 
                P\inv AP = \mat{
                    a -b;
                    b a
                    }
                and explain how to find a, b.

Find a 2 \times 2 real matrix A such that Av = \lambda v for \lambda = 2-3i and
                v = \mat{
                        2 + 2i;
                        1 - i
                    }

ol.li:
First we compute an element of \Nul(A−(1−i)I):
                        A-(1-i)I=\mat{-3+i 5; \star \star}
                        The second row is a multiple of the first, so an eigenvector is v = \vec{5 3-i}. Hence an eigenvector for 1+i is \bar v=\vec{5 3+i}.

C rotates by the argument of \bar λ=1+i:

                            \begin{tikzpicture}[every node/.style={font=\small, inner sep=1pt}]
                                \draw[help lines, black!30] (-.5,-.5) grid (1.5,1.5);
                                \point (o) at (0,0);
                                \draw[->] (-.5,0) -- (1.5,0);
                                \draw[->] (0,-.5) -- (0,1.5);
                                \coordinate (l) at (1,1);
                                \coordinate (x) at (1,0);
                                \draw[vector] (0,0) -- node[above left] {$\bar\lambda$} (1,1);
                                \pic[draw, "$\frac\pi4$", angle eccentricity=1.5]
                                {angle = x--o--l};
                                \node[font=\normalsize, right] at (3,.5)
                                {Argument of $\bar\lambda$ is $\frac\pi4$.};

                            \end{tikzpicture}
